-- PRESS DIGEST- Financial Times - Sept 17
-- 
-- Tue Sep 16, 2014 08:25PM EDT
-- None



Sept 17 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  AIRBUS TO STREAMLINE DEFENCE AND SPACE DIVISION THROUGH DISPOSALS (http://on.ft.com/ZoDxRj)  OPERATORS IN TALKS TO ACQUIRE PHONES 4U (http://on.ft.com/1t9xzim)  COURT LIFTS BAN ON UBER IN GERMANY (http://on.ft.com/1mcbKO6)   HONG KONG TYCOON PLACES RECORD $20 MLN ORDER FOR 30 ROLLS-ROYCES (http://on.ft.com/1qdiA0O)  UK PENSION FUND CRITICISES HEDGE FUND FEES (http://on.ft.com/1u4j0KN)  Overview  Airbus Group <AIR.PA> said on Tuesday it would sell its non-core businesses with revenues of more than 2 billion euros ($2.59 billion) to focus on its defence and space division on military aircraft, missiles and satellites.   Mobile operators EE and Vodafone Group Plc <VOD.L> which withdrew their business with Phones 4u last few weeks are in talks individually with the administrator to acquire parts of Phones 4u's business, including some of its stores, employees and shares across Britain.  The Frankfurt regional court issued a countrywide ban on Uber's ride-sharing service in Germany, ruling that taxi drivers had waited too long to seek an emergency call. The court threatened to fine up to 250,000 euros ($323,875) for each trip taken by Uber drivers in violation of the ban.   Hong Kong business tycoon Stephen Hung has made an order to purchase 30 Rolls-Royce Holdings Plc <RR.L> motor vehicles for $20 million to ferry guests at his new Macau gaming complex.  A British public pension fund has criticised hedge fund fees as unjustifiable, adding to industry tensions a day after California-based public pension fund Calpers said it had terminated its hedge fund programme.